        <section id="Mahalakshmi Temple (Ambabai Mandir)" class="section">
            <h2>Mahalakshmi Temple (Ambabai Mandir)</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Mahalakshmi Temple (Ambabai Mandir)" class="section-image">
            <p>The Mahalakshmi Temple, also known as Ambabai Mandir, in Kolhapur, is a significant Hindu temple dedicated to Goddess Mahalakshmi (also worshipped as Ambabai). It's one of the 18 Maha Shakti Peethas and is believed to be a place where desires are fulfilled and salvation can be attained. The temple is known for its architecture, dating back to the 7th century, possibly built during the Chalukya reign, and its gemstone idol of the goddess. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="New Palace & Shahu Museum" class="section">
            <h2>New Palace & Shahu Museum</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="New Palace & Shahu Museum" class="section-image">
            <p>The New Palace in Kolhapur, also known as the Chhatrapati Shahu Palace, is a testament to Maratha grandeur and architectural splendor. Constructed between 1877 and 1884, it was designed by British architect Charles Mant as the residence for the royal family. The palace exhibits a captivating fusion of Indo-Saracenic and Renaissance architectural styles, evident in its black polished stone structure, eight-angled design with a central tower, Neo-Mughal arches, temple-like brackets, and ornate balconies and domes adorned with intricate carvings. The palace also boasts a grand Darbar Hall, featuring double-height vistas, elaborately carved columns, and stained glass depicting scenes from the life of Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj</p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Rankala Lake" class="section">
            <h2>Rankala Lake</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Rankala Lake" class="section-image">
            <p>Initially, Rankala was a stone quarry. In the 9th century, a powerful earthquake caused water to accumulate from an underground source, ultimately leading to the formation of the lake. There's also a local belief that the lake was constructed by Chhatrapati Shahu Maharaj, according to Kolhapur.gov.in. The lake is also steeped in legend, with tales about a submerged Rankabhairav temple dedicated to Lord Shiva and a Nandi statue that is believed to be slowly moving towards the lake, hinting at the potential beginning of the apocalypse when it reaches it. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Panhala Fort" class="section">
            <h2>Panhala Fort</h2>
            <img src="https://www.madhutravels.in/images/d7.jpg" alt="Panhala Fort" class="section-image">
            <p>Panhala Fort, also known as Panhalgad, Panhalla, or Panalla, is a sprawling hill fort located about 20 kilometers northwest of Kolhapur, Maharashtra, India. It stands as a magnificent testament to Maharashtra's rich history, architectural prowess, and strategic significance, perched atop a hill in the Sahyadri mountain range. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Kopeshwar Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Kopeshwar Temple</h2>
            <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcRJGYPZcur0AfIDwiKs5yYkM-dFiLJ-rbaWWA&s" alt="Kopeshwar Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>The Kopeshwar Temple, located in Khidrapur, Kolhapur, is an ancient Hindu temple dedicated to Lord Shiva. It's known for its unique architecture, intricate carvings, and historical significance, showcasing the craftsmanship of the Chalukya and Rashtrakuta periods. The temple is divided into four main parts: Swargamandapam, Sabhamandapam, Antaral Kaksha, and Garbha Griha, all interconnected by vestibules. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Jyotiba Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Jyotiba Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Jyotiba Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>Jyotiba Temple, also known as Dakshinacha Raja (King of the South), is a revered Hindu temple located in Kolhapur, Maharashtra. It's dedicated to Lord Jyotiba, an incarnation of Lord Shiva, Vishnu, and Brahma. The temple is situated atop Jyotiba (Wadi Ratnagiri) Hill, offering panoramic views. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Bhavani Mandap" class="section">
            <h2>Bhavani Mandap</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Bhavani Mandap" class="section-image">
            <p>Bhavani Mandap is a historic building in Kolhapur, Maharashtra, India, known for its royal and religious significance. It was constructed between 1785 and 1800 and served as a gathering place for court officials and a venue for celebrations. The building also houses a temple dedicated to the goddess Tulja Bhavani. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Kaneri Siddhagiri Gramjivan Museum" class="section">
            <h2>Kaneri Siddhagiri Gramjivan Museum</h2>
            <img src="https://siddhagirimatham.org/public/images/frontend/Matham-Entrance-2.png" alt="Kaneri Siddhagiri Gramjivan Museum" class="section-image">
            <p>The Siddhagiri Gramjivan Museum, also known as Kaneri Math, is a unique museum located in Kaneri, near Kolhapur, Maharashtra. It showcases rural village life through intricately crafted wax and cement statues within the Shri Kshetra Siddhagiri Math. The museum is spread over 7 acres and is known for its lush greenery and countryside setting. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Radhanagari (Dajipur) Wildlife Sanctuary" class="section">
            <h2>Radhanagari (Dajipur) Wildlife Sanctuary</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Radhanagari (Dajipur) Wildlife Sanctuary" class="section-image">
            <p>Radhanagari (Dajipur) Wildlife Sanctuary, located in Kolhapur, Maharashtra, is a popular destination for wildlife enthusiasts. It is also known as Dajipur Bison Sanctuary and was the first wildlife sanctuary established in the state. The sanctuary is renowned for its diverse flora and fauna, particularly its population of Indian bison (gaur). </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Pohale (Pawala) Caves" class="section">
            <h2>Pohale (Pawala) Caves</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Pohale (Pawala) Caves" class="section-image">
            <p>Pohale Caves, also known as Pawala Caves, are a group of Buddhist caves located near Jyotiba's hill, about 15 km northeast of Kolhapur in Maharashtra, India. These caves are an important archaeological site with potential for tourism. They are characterized by a large vihara (monastery) with 14 columns and 22 cells, a chaitya (prayer hall), and a cave with a raised seat for a teacher, along with water cisterns. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>
